 BY BAMIDELE FAMOOFO Turnover in the Fixed Income and Currencies market increased by 29.9% or N4.73trillion, to stand at N20.54trillion, in December, 2021. The market closed on a positive note in the financial year ended December 31, 2021 with turnover increasing by about 32% representing an increase of N4.96trilllion compared to the figure in December 2020. Total Foreign Exchange (FX) market turnover in December 2021 was $16.37bn (N6.84trn), representing a MoM increase of 58.96% ($6.07bn) from the turnover recorded in November 2021 ($10.30bn). In the FX Market, the Naira depreciated against the US Dollar, losing 0.45% ($/N1.89) to close at an average of $/N416.81 in December 2021 from $/N414.92 recorded in November 2021, trading within a range of $/N414.06 â€“ $/N435.00. The MoM increase in total FX market turnover was jointly driven by the 55.33% ($3.10bn) and 63.29% ($2.98bn) MoM increase in FX Spot and FX Derivatives turnover respectively in December 2021. The MoM increase in FX Derivatives turnover was driven by MoM increase in turnover for FX Swaps and FX Futures by 188.79% ($2.91bn) and 16.43% ($0.10bn) respectively; despite the 1.55% ($0.04bn) decrease in FX Forwards.  Consequently, the contribution of FX Derivatives to total FX market turnover increased by 1.24percentage points (ppts) to 46.88% in December 2021. In the OTC FX Futures market, the near month contract5 (NGUS DEC 29, 2021) expired and open positions with a total notional value (NV) of $0.55bn were settled. A far month (60M6) contract, NGUS DEC 30, 2026 was introduced at a Futures price of $/N614.32. The total NV of open OTC FX Futures contracts as at December 31, 2021 stood at circa $5.33bn7 representing a MoM decrease of 2.20% ($0.12bn) from its value as at November 30, 2021. 